1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Yo. I'm going to tell you
something that cost me weeks.

2
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Real weeks.

3
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Not "I lost a couple hours" weeks.

4
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I mean full rebuilds.

5
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Started-over-from-scratch weeks.

6
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And nobody warned me
it was coming.

7
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I run five businesses
out of West Palm Beach.

8
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
A restaurant.

9
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
A courier company.

10
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
A trading education brand.

11
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
A content funnel engine.

12
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And the legal structure
holding it all together.

13
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
All under one roof
called MysterMyself.

14
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Scott-King Coast. One ecosystem.

15
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And I decided to let AI run
the day-to-day operations.

16
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Not just one AI.
A whole team of them.

17
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Claude for strategy.
Kiro for code.

18
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Cowork for desktop automation.
The whole stack working together.

19
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Sounds futuristic right? It is.

20
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Until you hit the wall.

21
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Here's the thing nobody
warns you about.

22
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
These AI agents?
They don't remember anything.

23
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Nothing. Zero.

24
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You have a two hour session.

25
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You build something incredible.

26
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You map out your whole system.

27
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You explain your brand.
Your characters. Your colors.

28
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Your rules. You go deep.

29
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You explain that Trading Chef
is the avatar.

30
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You explain the six districts.

31
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You explain the ten characters.

32
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Everything is perfect.
The agent understands.

33
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You're cooking.

34
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Then you close that window.

35
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And it's gone. All of it. Erased.

36
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Next session? That agent has
no idea who you are.

37
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No idea what you built yesterday.

38
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No idea that your brand color
is Gold, not yellow.

39
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No idea that your handle
is @mysterycartel.

40
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No idea that you have ten locked
characters that cannot be changed.

41
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No idea that you already built
half the website.

42
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It just starts fresh.
Every single time.

43
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Like you never met.

44
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I'm not exaggerating.

45
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I lost entire product builds
because an agent invented

46
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
new characters that don't exist
in my world.

47
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It changed my color palette
without asking.

48
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Called my brand the wrong name.

49
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Made up features I never approved.

50
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Added a seventh district
when I only have six.

51
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Created an eleventh character
when I only have ten.

52
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And the worst part?

53
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I didn't catch it until
three sessions later.

54
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
By then everything
was tangled up.

55
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I had code referencing things
that shouldn't exist.

56
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Pages built for characters
nobody created.

57
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The whole thing was a mess.

58
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
That's the problem.
AI has amnesia.

59
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And if you're building anything
serious with it,

60
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
anything with a brand,
characters, rules, a world...

61
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
that amnesia will destroy
your work quietly.

62
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You won't even notice
until it's too late.

63
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
So I fixed it.

64
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I built my own system
from scratch.

65
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Three pieces that work together.

66
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And it changed everything
about how I use AI.

67
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
That's what this series is about.

68
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I'm calling it
The Claude Chronicles.

69
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Let's get into it.

70
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
First thing I built was what I
call canon anchors.

71
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
This is the foundation.

72
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Without this, nothing else works.

73
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Think about it like this.

74
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You're building a world.
Not just a product. A world.

75
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I'm building Scott-King Coast.

76
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It has six districts.

77
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Route Harbor
for courier operations.

78
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Market Marina
for trading education.

79
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Flavor District for food.

80
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Blueprint Bay for legal.

81
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Creator Pier for content.

82
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Legacy Point
for intellectual property.

83
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Six districts. Each one locked.

84
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It has characters. Trading Chef.

85
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
That's my avatar.

86
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Black male, chef hat, apron,
gold chain, glasses.

87
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Confident. Urban cartoon style.

88
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Then there's Candle Kid. Wickie.

89
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Louie Liquidity. Chef Goldie.

90
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Grandma Market. Nana Value.

91
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Melissa Mayhem. Melody Mayhem.

92
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Rico Rhythm. Ten characters total.

93
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Each one locked. No agent
can invent an eleventh.

94
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It has colors.
Black. Gold. Red. Green.

95
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Fire Orange. That's the palette.

96
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Locked.

97
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No agent can decide "hey let's
add some blue in there." No.

98
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It has rules.

99
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The handle is always
@mysterycartel.

100
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The avatar always has the chef
hat, the apron, the gold chain.

101
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Always urban cartoon style.

102
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The brand name is always
MysterMyself.

103
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No abbreviations.
No alternate spellings.

104
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No nicknames.

105
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
None of that can change without
my explicit approval. Period.

106
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
So what did I do?

107
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I wrote it all down in one file.

108
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
A canon document.
One source of truth.

109
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And I told every single agent
in my system:

110
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
before you do anything,

111
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
before you write one line
of code,

112
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
before you draft one piece
of content, read this file first.

113
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
If what you're about to create
contradicts this file

114
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
in any way, stop. Don't do it.

115
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
That's a canon anchor.

116
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It's a fixed point in space
that cannot drift.

117
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No matter how creative
the AI wants to get,

118
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
it has boundaries. It has laws.

119
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Before I had this? Chaos.

120
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Agents would invent characters
I never created.

121
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
They'd add districts
that don't exist.

122
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
They'd change my slogan.

123
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
They'd use the wrong handle.

124
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
They'd describe my avatar
without the gold chain.

125
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Small things. Tiny details.

126
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
But they compound into a mess
that takes days to untangle.

127
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Now? The canon is law.

128
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The agents read it at the start
of every session.

129
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
They cannot drift because
the anchor holds them in place.

130
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Like a ship tied to a dock.

131
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The water moves. The ship stays.

132
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Simple concept.
Not complicated to implement.

133
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
But it changed everything about
the quality of what my agents

134
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
produce.

135
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Canon anchors solve
the "what is true" problem.

136
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
But there's a second problem
that's just as bad.

137
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The "where were we" problem.

138
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Let me paint the picture.

139
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Monday I'm working with Kiro
on the website.

140
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
We fix three bugs
on the homepage.

141
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
We update the navigation to
include all six districts.

142
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
We start building a new page
for the Trading Chef

143
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
tutorial system
but don't finish it.

144
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Good session. Productive.
We made progress.

145
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Tuesday I come back.
Open a new session.

146
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The agent doesn't know
any of that happened.

147
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It doesn't know
what bugs we fixed.

148
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Doesn't know
the navigation changed.

149
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Doesn't know there's a
half-built page sitting

150
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
in the codebase.

151
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
As far as it knows,
nothing happened yesterday.

152
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
So what does it do? It guesses.

153
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It looks at the code and tries
to figure out the current state.

154
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Or worse, it starts suggesting
things we already tried.

155
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It re-introduces bugs
we already fixed.

156
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It suggests building a page
that already half-exists.

157
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It proposes changes to code
that already changed.

158
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
You end up going backwards.

159
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Undoing progress.
Fighting your own system.

160
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Session state management
solves this.

161
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And it's simpler than you think.

162
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Here's how I do it.

163
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
At the end of every working
session, the agent writes

164
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
a memory block. Plain English.

165
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
What was built. What was changed.

166
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
What files were modified.

167
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
What's still pending.

168
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
What was approved by me.
What was rejected by me.

169
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
What needs to happen next.

170
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It's like shift notes
at a restaurant.

171
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The dinner crew writes down
what happened during their shift

172
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
so the morning crew
knows what's up.

173
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No surprises. No repeated work.

174
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Next session starts?

175
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
First thing the agent does
is read those memory blocks.

176
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The latest entries.

177
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It knows exactly
where we left off.

178
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
What we accomplished.
What's still open.

179
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No guessing. No repeating work.

180
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No re-introducing bugs
we already squashed.

181
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I keep these in a file
called MEMORY-BLOCKS.

182
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It's a running log
in the docs folder.

183
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Every session adds to it.

184
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The agent reads the latest
entries and picks up

185
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
like we never stopped talking.

186
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Like a real person
coming back from lunch.

187
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
They don't forget the entire
morning just because

188
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
they ate a sandwich.

189
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It's not complicated technology.

190
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It's just discipline baked
into the system.

191
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The system writes its own
context at the end.

192
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The system reads its own
context at the start.

193
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The human, that's me,

194
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
doesn't have to repeat
themselves every single session.

195
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I don't have to
re-explain my brand.

196
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I don't have to re-explain
what we built yesterday.

197
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The system already knows.

198
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
That's session state management.

199
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Your AI picks up where
it left off. Every time.

200
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Automatically.

201
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Here's where it gets
really interesting.

202
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I don't use one agent.
I use four. Working together.

203
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Like a team.

204
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Claude handles strategy.

205
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Big picture thinking. Writing.
Planning.

206
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Architecture decisions.

207
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
When I need to think through
a problem or plan a new feature,

208
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
that's Claude.

209
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Kiro handles code.

210
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Building features.
Git operations. Pull requests.

211
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Pushing to production.

212
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
When something needs to get
built and deployed, that's Kiro.

213
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Cowork handles my desktop.

214
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Moving files between folders.
Opening applications.

215
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Local file management.

216
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Anything that requires touching
my actual computer,

217
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
that's Cowork.

218
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
GitHub is the source of truth.
The repo.

219
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Everything lives there.

220
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
If it's not in the repo,
it doesn't exist.

221
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Four agents. One system.

222
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And they have to talk to each
other without me

223
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
playing telephone.

224
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
That's relay agent architecture.

225
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It works exactly
like a relay race.

226
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
One runner does their leg
of the track.

227
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Then they pass the baton
to the next runner.

228
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Clean handoff. Full speed.

229
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
No dropped context.
No fumbled baton.

230
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Here's how a real task flows
through my system.

231
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I tell Claude what I want.

232
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
"Build me a thumbnail system
for the YouTube channel."

233
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Claude thinks about it.
Writes the strategy.

234
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Figures out the file structure.

235
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Defines the acceptance criteria.

236
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Then Claude drops a relay task
into an inbox folder

237
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
on my desktop.

238
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Kiro picks up that relay task.
Reads it.

239
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Has everything it needs.

240
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The what. The why.
The constraints.

241
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
The exact files to create.

242
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Kiro executes. Writes the code.

243
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Pushes it to a branch.
Creates a pull request.

244
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Reports back.

245
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I never touch the terminal.

246
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Never type a git command.

247
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Never open VS Code.
Never install a package.

248
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
I just say what I want
in plain English

249
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
and the relay handles the rest.

250
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
But here's the key
that makes it work.

251
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Each agent knows its role
and only its role.

252
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Claude doesn't try
to write code.

253
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Kiro doesn't try to do strategy.

254
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Cowork doesn't try
to push to GitHub.

255
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
They stay in their lane.
No overlap. No confusion.

256
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
And the handoff document?

257
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
That relay task? That's the baton.

258
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
It contains everything the next
agent needs to execute

259
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
